# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "Iron Rations 3 -> 1; meat drop 70% -> 55% (build 379). Rolling back the last two pieces of the b327 sparse-food tuning cascade (the others -- 0.7/move hunger decay and 5-ration starter -- reverted in b374 and b378 respectively). Direct vendor inspection on b378 showed per-vendor food still at 295-345 nut, with Iron Rations alone contributing 210 nut (~60-70% of the food calories). Iron Rations stack cut 3 -> 1 (vendor.py:300) brings the per-vendor stack to 155-205 nut. Meat drop rate 70% -> 55% (items.py:3219): b327 bumped this to 70% specifically `alongside the slower hunger decay and bigger Iron Rations stash`, both of which are gone. At 70% / 22 kills per run agents averaged ~16 meat drops, which combined with the ration supply made cooking and sausage decisions optional. 55% (~12 meat/run) keeps meat the dominant kill reward but makes raw-vs-cooked and craft-now-vs-later real tactical choices. Smoke-tested: median food/vendor 5-6 -> 3 items, meat drop sample 55.2% over 1000 trials.",
    "Vendor Rations 3-4 -> 1-2; restore starter pack to 5 (build 378). Build 377 cut starter rations 5 -> 3 alongside dropping the Curing Kit gate F10 -> F5, but the user feedback was that the abundance problem is on the dungeon-vendor side, not the starter pack: agents need the pre-F2-vendor buffer. Rolled the starter pack back to 5 (both vendor.py:starting_shop and playtest_harness.py:starter_pack) and instead cut the per-vendor Rations stack from `random.randint(3, 4)` -> `random.randint(1, 2)` at vendor.py:286. Per-vendor food payload now: 1-2 Rations (50-100 nut) + 3 Iron Rations (210 nut) + 1 Jerky (35 nut) = 295-345 nut, vs. b376's 395-445 nut. With smart-policy buying every food stack on every visit and 5-10 vendor visits per long run, total ration accumulation drops from 19-53 -> ~5-20 per run. Iron Rations and Salted Jerky stacks unchanged -- the cut targets the cheap-bulk-hoard problem, not the meaningful nutrition tiers.",
    "Curing Kit F10 -> F5; starter rations 5 -> 3 (build 377). Playtest-376 sweep diagnosis: crafting works ~100% once the kit is owned (4/4 kit-holders crafted at least one sausage, including a dwarf making Landjäger with rare Iron Bark), but only 4/18 runs ever got a kit -- the F10 gate placed the relief valve AFTER the F2-F5 starvation cliff. Hunger-decay tuning (b374 1.0/move) was killing 4-6 runs per sweep BEFORE the crafting layer was reachable. Drop the Curing Kit gate to F5+ (vendor.py:Vendor.__init__ z >= 4 and items.py:generate_vendor_inventory floor_level >= 4) so the kit lands on the same floor band where hunger pressure starts biting. Also trimmed starter rations 5 -> 3 in BOTH the starting shop (vendor.py:129) AND the playtest starter-pack mirror (playtest_harness.py:583): the b376 sweep showed peak inventory nutrition still hitting 1560-3315 across the run, so 5 rations was making F1-F4 food economy decorative. Three rations = 150 nutrition cushion (vs 250 before), still meaningful for the agent's pre-F2-vendor buffer but no longer guaranteeing the F2-F5 floors are skipped. Combined effect: shifts the food clock's bite-zone to overlap with the crafting layer, so the sausage / lembas relief valves can actually fire for at-risk agents. Smoke-tested: F4 vendor has no kit, F5 vendor stocks one, second F5 vendor (pre-purchase) also stocks one, post-purchase vendors stop. Starter pack ships 3 rations instead of 5.",
    "Dwarven sausages + elven lembas crafting (build 376). Added two race-locked sausage recipes via a new `'race'` field on the recipe dict, filtered in game_systems.get_available_recipes(): (1) Landjäger -- Alpine air-dried hunter's sausage, 1 cooked meat + Fire Root + Iron Bark -> 100 nut, tier 2, dwarf-only. (2) Blutwurst -- iron-rich German blood sausage, 2 cooked meat + Healing Moss + Stone Flower -> 140 nut, tier 3, dwarf-only. Both pair with the Sausage.use() +50% dwarf bonus (items.py:2955), so a dwarf eating Blutwurst gets a 210-equivalent meal in one turn. Iron Bark and Stone Flower are rare garden drops (2% each), so dwarven sausages read as treasure-tier crafts the way the persona-flavor wants. Also wired smart-policy lembas crafting for elves: existing LEMBAS_RECIPES (item_templates.py:218) were already there but the policy had no trigger. Generalized _pick_craftable_sausage -> _pick_craftable_food, which scores recipes by (priority_bucket, tier): bucket 0 = race-locked sausage, bucket 1 = lembas (gated to ration_count >= 2), bucket 2 = generic sausage. Inventory trigger now fires on either pathway (sausage path = Curing Kit + cooked meat; lembas path = elf race + ingredients). Lembas Wafer fills hunger to max AND freezes decay for 30 turns -- the single most powerful food item in the game; crafting one trades 3 herbs + 1 ration for 100 nut + 30 free turns. Smoke-tested: dwarf with Landjäger materials picks Landjäger over Bratwurst; human with Iron Bark sees only Bratwurst (Landjäger correctly hidden); elf with Moonpetal+Healing Moss picks Lembas Wafer over Healing Potion.",
    "Smart policy now crafts sausages (build 375). Playtest-374 sweep found the Curing Kit was reliably bought at F10+ (4/4) but the sausage subsystem was still dead -- the policy had no craft trigger and the harness had no `crafting_mode` dispatch, so 0 sausages were ever made across the run. Three pieces landed: (1) harness step() now routes `crafting_mode` to game_systems.process_crafting_action. (2) New `_pick_craftable_sausage()` helper mirrors process_crafting_action's recipe-number lookup by calling get_available_recipes(pc) and indexing the live `craftable` list (filtered to r[2]==True), so the action number we return matches the menu the game shows. (3) Inventory dispatcher adds a craft trigger right after the cook-kit gate: if has Curing Kit + has cooked Meat + has ingredients for at least one non-spicy recipe + hunger >= 30, return 'c' (enter crafting_mode). The crafting_mode policy handler picks the lowest-tier non-spicy recipe (Bratwurst > Chorizo > Andouille > Boerewors) and crafts; once nothing remains craftable, returns 'x' to exit. Spicy variants (Pepperwurst / Diablo Chorizo / Dragonbreath) are skipped -- they consume Fire Pepper / Ghost Pepper at 1-3% garden spawn rate, hoarded for a future buff-aware policy. Sausage math vs alternatives: Bratwurst = 60 nut from 1 cooked meat + 2 common herbs (Moonpetal + Fire Root); plain cooked meat eats at 18 nut, so the craft yields 3.3x nutrition per meat. Dwarves get a hidden +50% bonus from Sausage.use() (items.py:2955), making Bratwurst worth 90 nut + 7.5 HP for a dwarf. Also added 'ingredient' category in _item_category so the harness obs surfaces garden herbs cleanly.",
    "Bump hunger decay 0.7 -> 1.0 per move to make the food clock bite (build 374). Playtest-372/373 validation showed the food clock was decorative: F1-F3 mean hunger 74.5, F4-F6 70.8, 0/18 runs ever crossed the Hungry threshold (40), 0/18 starvation deaths despite peak inventory nutrition holding at 1560 across the sweep. The 0.7/move rate dates from build 327, when the food economy was much sparser -- since then Iron Rations stack went 1->3 (b328), F1 dungeon vendors got Rations + Iron Rations (b328), and the starter pack added Cooking Kit + extra rations. With ~410 nut per vendor visit vs. ~210 at the time of the original tuning, going back to 1/move (the pre-b327 default, +43% decay rate) should restore real hunger pressure without re-introducing the F3-F4 starvation gate. Concrete impact: 60 turns from full hunger -> Hungry threshold (was 86), 90 turns -> Starving (was 129), 100 turns -> 0 (was 143). Tracker pair (HUNGER_DECAY_PER_MOVE=10 / HUNGER_DECAY_INTERVAL=10 = 1.0 flat) keeps decay integer.",
    "Curing Kit reliability: every F10+ regular vendor stocks one until purchased (build 373). Playtest-372 validation sweep (18 runs) found 2/5 F9+ first-vendor encounters skipped the kit because the vendor was a bug merchant -- the bug_merchant=True branch in Vendor.__init__ returns early before reaching the Curing Kit gate. Rather than duplicate the gate in the bug-merchant branch, switched to the cleaner 'every F10+ regular vendor stocks one until the player buys it' pattern: the gs.curing_kit_stocked one-shot flag now flips in the buy handler (vendor.py:process_vendor_action) on actual purchase, NOT on stocking. Effect: a player who walks past or only sees bug-merchant F10 vendors will still find the kit at the next F10+ regular vendor. Also bumped the floor gate F9 -> F10 (z >= 9): 78% of bug levels still spawn at F8-F10 (probability table: F8 40%, F9 24%, F10 14.4%, ...) so F10 stays the natural mid-game milestone, and in playtest mode where bug-level is always F8 the kit lands cleanly post-bug.",
    "Shrink auto-unequips normal-size gear (build 360). User-reported bug: Bombur Axebreaker (s=10 dwarf) wound up with Adamantine Armor + Scorpion Tail Whip co-equipped -- normal-size armor and bug-size weapon at the same time. Root cause: the equip gate at game_systems.py:2263 only blocks NEW equips of the wrong size, not gear that was already equipped before the size change. _restore_size_on_bug_exit already drops bug gear when growing back, but the SHRINK direction had no symmetric unequip -- so a player descending into a bug floor in full Adamantine kit kept the armor through the shrink, then swapped the weapon slot to a bug weapon and ended up in a mixed state. Fix: _trigger_shrinking_spell now unequips any non-bug Weapon/Armor at the moment of shrinking, with flavor logs ('suddenly enormous in your tiny hands', 'slides off your shrunken frame'). Items stay in inventory so they auto-re-equip on grow-back.",
]
